Any curvature issues will mess it up.
There are a lot of challenges  

559
00:49:26,240 --> 00:49:29,760
with scaling the production.
It's quite artisanal in this sense  

560
00:49:29,760 --> 00:49:34,240
because you're not making tens of thousands 
of these a year, you're making hundreds,  

561
00:49:34,240 --> 00:49:43,600
you're making thousands. 60 tools a year, 18 of 
these per tool, you’re still in the hundreds,  

562
00:49:43,600 --> 00:49:50,800
of tools, or you're at the thousand number 
roughly for these lenses and projection optics. 

563
00:49:51,440 --> 00:49:57,200
Then you step forward to the reticle stage, 
which is also something really crazy. 

564
00:49:57,200 --> 00:50:03,120
This thing moves at, I want to say, nine Gs.
It will shift nine Gs because as you step  

565
00:50:03,120 --> 00:50:07,360
across a wafer, the tool will go... The 
wafer stage is complementary. It's the  

566
00:50:07,360 --> 00:50:11,120
wafer part. You line these two things up.
You're taking all the light through the  

567
00:50:11,120 --> 00:50:14,480
lenses that's focused, and here's 
the reticle, here's the wafer. 

568
00:50:16,160 --> 00:50:20,000
The reticle's moving one direction, the 
wafer's moving the other direction as it  

569
00:50:20,000 --> 00:50:25,680
scans a 26x33 millimeter section 
of the wafer, and then it stops. 

570
00:50:25,680 --> 00:50:28,800
It shifts over to another part 
of the wafer and does it again. 

571
00:50:28,800 --> 00:50:32,000
It does that in just seconds.
Each of them is moving  

572
00:50:32,000 --> 00:50:37,040
at nine Gs in opposite directions.
Each of these things is a wonder and marvel  

573
00:50:37,040 --> 00:50:47,200
of chemistry, fabrication, mechanical engineering, 
and optical engineering, because you have to align  

574
00:50:47,200 --> 00:50:50,640
all these things and make sure they're perfect.
All of these things have crazy amounts  

575
00:50:50,640 --> 00:50:53,280
of metrology because you have 
to perfectly test everything. 

576
00:50:53,280 --> 00:50:58,640
If anything is messed up, the yield goes to 
zero, because this is such a finely tuned system. 

577
00:50:58,640 --> 00:51:05,920
By the way, it's so large that you're building 
it in the factory in Eindhoven, Netherlands,  

578
00:51:05,920 --> 00:51:10,640
and they're deconstructing it and shipping it on 
many planes to the customer site, and then you're  

579
00:51:10,640 --> 00:51:14,400
reassembling it there and testing it again.
That process takes many, many months. 

580
00:51:15,680 --> 00:51:19,760
There are so many steps in the supply 
chain, whether it's Zeiss making their  

581
00:51:19,760 --> 00:51:25,280
lenses and projection optics or Cymer, which is 
an ASML-owned company, making the EUV source. 

582
00:51:25,280 --> 00:51:29,760
Each of these has its own complex supply chain.
ASML has commented that their supply chain has  

583
00:51:29,760 --> 00:51:32,400
over ten thousand people in it.
Like individual suppliers? 

584
00:51:32,400 --> 00:51:37,040
Yes. It might not be directly. It might 
be through Zeiss having so many suppliers  

585
00:51:37,040 --> 00:51:44,080
and XYZ company having so many suppliers.
If you just think about it, you're talking  

586
00:51:44,080 --> 00:51:51,920
about two physically moving objects that are 
the size of a wafer, and it has to be accurate  

587
00:51:51,920 --> 00:51:58,720
to the level of single-digit nanometers or even 
smaller because the entire system, the overlay,  

588
00:51:58,720 --> 00:52:03,200
the layer-to-layer overlay variation, 
has to be on the order of 3 nanometers. 

589
00:52:04,720 --> 00:52:09,360
If the overlay is 3 nms, that means each 
individual part, the accuracy of its  

590
00:52:09,360 --> 00:52:14,160
physical movement has to be even less than that.
It has to be sub-one nanometer in most cases,  

591
00:52:14,160 --> 00:52:23,360
because the error of these things stack up.
There's no way to just snap your fingers and  

592
00:52:23,360 --> 00:52:27,920
increase production. Things as simple as power. 
The US going from zero percent power growth to  

593
00:52:27,920 --> 00:52:32,400
two percent power growth, even though China's 
already at thirty, was so hard for America to do. 

594
00:52:34,240 --> 00:52:41,920
And that's a really simple supply chain with 
very few people in it who make difficult things. 

595
00:52:41,920 --> 00:52:45,920
There are probably 100,000 
electricians and people who work in  

596
00:52:45,920 --> 00:52:53,920
the electricity supply chain, or more, in the US?
When you look at ASML, they employ so few people. 

597
00:52:53,920 --> 00:52:58,480
Carl Zeiss probably employs less than a 
thousand people working on this, and all of  

598
00:52:58,480 --> 00:53:02,960
those people are super, super specialized.
You can't just train random people up  

599
00:53:02,960 --> 00:53:06,720
for this in the snap of a finger.
You can't just get your entire supply  

600
00:53:06,720 --> 00:53:10,240
chain to get galvanized.
Nvidia's had to do a lot  

601
00:53:11,600 --> 00:53:15,920
to get the entire supply chain to even deliver 
the capacity they're going to make this year. 

602
00:53:15,920 --> 00:53:18,800
When you go talk to Anthropic, they're 
like, "We're short of TPUs, we're short  

603
00:53:18,800 --> 00:53:21,200
of training, and we're short of GPUs."
When you go talk to OpenAI, they're like,  

604
00:53:21,200 --> 00:53:25,640
"We're short of these things."
OpenAI and Anthropic know they need X. 

605
00:53:25,640 --> 00:53:31,920
Nvidia is not quite as AGI-pilled. 
They're building X - 1. You go down the  

606
00:53:31,920 --> 00:53:35,760
supply chain, everyone's doing X - 1.
In some cases, they're doing X ÷ 2,  

607
00:53:36,480 --> 00:53:42,000
because they're not AGI-pilled.
You end up with this time lag  

608
00:53:42,000 --> 00:53:48,640
for the whip to react.
The AI-pilledness and the  

609
00:53:48,640 --> 00:53:53,680
desire to increase production takes so long.
Once they finally understand that they need  

610
00:53:53,680 --> 00:53:57,120
to increase production rapidly… 
They think they understand. 

611
00:53:57,120 --> 00:54:01,200
They think AI means we have to go from 60 
to 100, in addition to the tools getting  

612
00:54:01,200 --> 00:54:05,200
better and faster, the source getting 
higher power from 500 watts to 1,000,  

613
00:54:05,200 --> 00:54:09,760
and all these other aspects of the supply chain 
advancing technically and increasing production. 

614
00:54:09,760 --> 00:54:13,040
They think they're actually 
increasing production a lot. 

615
00:54:13,040 --> 00:54:15,920
But if you flow through the 
numbers… What does Elon want? 

616
00:54:15,920 --> 00:54:21,360
He wants 100 gigawatts a year 
in space by 2028 or 2029. 

617
00:54:23,040 --> 00:54:27,520
Sam Altman wants 52 gigawatts a 
year by the end of the decade. 

618
00:54:28,400 --> 00:54:32,000
Anthropic probably needs the 
same, and Google needs that. 

619
00:54:32,000 --> 00:54:35,440
You go across the supply chain, and it's 
like, wait, no, the supply chain can't  

620
00:54:35,440 --> 00:54:41,200
possibly build enough capacity for everyone 
to get what they want on the side of compute. 

621
00:55:44,800 --> 00:55:50,640
I feel like in the data center 
supply chain for the last few years,  

622
00:55:50,640 --> 00:55:55,040
people have been making arguments like, "We are 
bottlenecked by this specific thing, therefore  

623
00:55:55,040 --> 00:56:00,400
AI compute can't scale more than X."
But as you've written about, if the  

624
00:56:00,400 --> 00:56:06,800
grid is a bottleneck, then we just do behind the 
meter on the site, we do gas turbines, et cetera. 

625
00:56:06,800 --> 00:56:10,880
If that doesn't work, there are all these 
other alternatives that people fall back on. 

626
00:56:11,520 --> 00:56:17,920
I want to ask whether we can imagine a similar 
thing happening in the semiconductor supply chain. 

627
00:56:17,920 --> 00:56:24,000
If EUV becomes a bottleneck, what if we 
just went back to 7 nm and did what China  

628
00:56:24,000 --> 00:56:29,680
is doing currently, producing 7 nm chips 
with multi-patterning with DUV machines? 

629
00:56:31,520 --> 00:56:36,320
If you look at a 7 nm chip like the 
A100, there's been a lot of progress  

630
00:56:36,320 --> 00:56:44,800
obviously from the A100 to the B100 or B200.
How much of that progress is just numerics? 

631
00:56:45,600 --> 00:56:54,880
If you just hold FP16 constant from A100 to B100.
The B100 is a little over one petaflop, and the  

632
00:56:54,880 --> 00:57:02,080
A100 is like 300 teraflops.
Yeah, 312. 

633
00:57:02,720 --> 00:57:06,880
Holding numerics constant, you have 
a 3x improvement from A100 to B100. 

634
00:57:07,600 --> 00:57:11,680
Some of that is the process improvement, some of 
that is just the accelerator design improving,  

635
00:57:11,680 --> 00:57:16,960
which we could replicate again in the future.
It seems there's actually a very small effect  

636
00:57:16,960 --> 00:57:24,800
from the process improving from 7nm to 4 nm.
I don't know the numbers offhand but let's  

637
00:57:24,800 --> 00:57:31,040
say there's 150k wafers per month of 3 nm 
and eventually similar amounts for 2 nm. 

638
00:57:31,040 --> 00:57:36,560
But then there's a similar amount for 7 nm.
If you have all those old wafers and there's  

639
00:57:36,560 --> 00:57:43,920
maybe a 50% haircut because the bits per 
wafer area are 50% less or something,  

640
00:57:45,280 --> 00:57:50,560
it doesn't seem that bad to just bring on 7 
nm wafers if that gives you another fifty or  

641
00:57:50,560 --> 00:58:00,320
hundred gigawatts. Tell me why that's naive.
We potentially do go crazy enough that this  

642
00:58:01,200 --> 00:58:04,960
happens because we just need incremental 
compute, and the compute is worth the  

643
00:58:04,960 --> 00:58:13,440
higher cost and power of these chips.
But it's also unlikely to a large extent  

644
00:58:13,440 --> 00:58:22,400
because some of these are not fair comparisons.
For example, from A100, which is 312 teraflops,  

645
00:58:22,400 --> 00:58:31,680
to Blackwell, which is 1,000 or 2,000 FP16, 
and then Rubin is 5,000 or so FP16… It's not  

646
00:58:31,680 --> 00:58:38,400
a fair comparison because these chips 
have vastly different design targets. 

647
00:58:38,400 --> 00:58:45,440
With A100, Nvidia optimized 
for FP16 and BF16 numerics. 

648
00:58:45,440 --> 00:58:49,600
When you look at Hopper, they didn't care 
as much about that; they cared about FP8. 

649
00:58:49,600 --> 00:58:53,840
When you look at Rubin, they don’t 
care about FP16 and BF16 so much,  

650
00:58:53,840 --> 00:59:02,960
they care mostly about FP4 and FP6.
Numerics are what they've designed their chip for. 

651
00:59:06,800 --> 00:59:14,480
Let's say we make a new chip design on 7 nm, 
optimized for the numerics of the modern day. 

652
00:59:14,480 --> 00:59:16,480
The performance difference is 
still going to be much larger  

653
00:59:16,480 --> 00:59:23,200
than the FLOPS difference you mentioned.
Often it's easy to boil things down to FLOPS  

654
00:59:23,200 --> 00:59:28,000
per watt or FLOPS per dollar, 
but that's not a fair comparison. 

655
00:59:32,000 --> 00:59:40,480
Let's look at Kimi K2.5 and DeepSeek.
When you look at those two models and  

656
00:59:40,480 --> 00:59:45,520
their performance on Hopper versus 
Blackwell on very optimized software,  

657
00:59:45,520 --> 00:59:50,960
you get vastly different performance.
Most of this is not attributed to  

658
00:59:50,960 --> 00:59:55,200
FLOPS or numerics, because those 
models are actually eight-bit. 

659
00:59:55,200 --> 00:59:59,680
So it's not like Blackwells and Hopper are both 
optimized for eight-bit, and Blackwell is not  

660
00:59:59,680 --> 01:00:05,920
really taking advantage of its four-bit there.
The performance gulf is actually much larger. 

661
01:00:09,600 --> 01:00:14,160
Sure it's one thing to shrink process 
technology and make the transistor smaller  

662
01:00:14,160 --> 01:00:18,640
so each chip has X number of FLOPS, 
but you forget the big gating factor. 

663
01:00:18,640 --> 01:00:22,160
These models don't run on a single chip.
They run on hundreds of chips at a time. 

664
01:00:22,160 --> 01:00:25,360
If you look at DeepSeek's production 
deployment, which is well over a  

665
01:00:25,360 --> 01:00:31,360
year old now, they were running on 160 GPUs.
That's what they serve production traffic on. 

666
01:00:31,360 --> 01:00:35,520
They split the model across 160 GPUs.
Every time you cross the barrier from one  

667
01:00:35,520 --> 01:00:40,960
chip to another, there is an efficiency loss.
You have to transmit over high-speed  

668
01:00:40,960 --> 01:00:44,160
electrical SerDes, which brings 
a latency cost and a power cost. 

669
01:00:44,160 --> 01:00:51,280
There are all these dynamics that hurt.
As you shrink and shrink the process node, you've  

670
01:00:51,280 --> 01:01:01,360
increased the amount of compute in a single chip.
Now in-chip movement of data is at least tens  

671
01:01:01,360 --> 01:01:03,920
of terabytes a second, if not 
hundreds of terabytes a second. 

672
01:01:04,480 --> 01:01:07,840
Whereas between chips, you're on 
the order of a terabyte a second. 

673
01:01:09,680 --> 01:01:13,520
Then you have this movement of data between chips 
that are super close to each other physically. 

674
01:01:13,520 --> 01:01:15,840
You can only put so many chips 
close to each other physically,  

675
01:01:15,840 --> 01:01:20,720
so you have to put chips in different racks.
The movement of data between racks is on the order  

676
01:01:20,720 --> 01:01:26,800
of hundreds of gigabits a second, 400 gig or 800 
gig a second, so roughly 100 gigabytes a second. 

677
01:01:27,440 --> 01:01:32,800
So you have this huge ladder: on-chip 
communication is super fast, within the  

678
01:01:32,800 --> 01:01:39,520
rack is an order of magnitude slower, and outside 
the rack is an order of magnitude lower than that. 

679
01:01:39,520 --> 01:01:43,280
As you break the bounds of chips, 
you end up with a performance loss. 

680
01:01:43,280 --> 01:01:47,120
The reason I explain this is because 
when you look at Hopper versus Blackwell,  

681
01:01:47,120 --> 01:01:52,720
even if both are using a rack's worth of 
chips, Hopper is significantly slower. 

682
01:01:52,720 --> 01:02:00,160
The amount of performance you have leveraged to 
the task within each domain—tens of terabytes a  

683
01:02:00,160 --> 01:02:06,400
second of communication between these processing 
elements versus terabytes a second between these  

684
01:02:06,400 --> 01:02:11,600
processing elements—is much, much higher and 
therefore the performance is much higher. 

685
01:02:11,600 --> 01:02:18,000
When you look at inference at 100 tokens 
a second for DeepSeek and Kimi K2.5,  

686
01:02:19,120 --> 01:02:21,280
the performance difference between Hopper 
and Blackwell is on the order of 20x. 

687
01:02:21,280 --> 01:02:24,640
It's not 2x or 3x like the FLOPS 
performance difference indicates,  

688
01:02:24,640 --> 01:02:28,880
even though those are on the same process node.
There are just differences in networking  

689
01:02:28,880 --> 01:02:32,640
technologies and what they've worked on.
You can translate some of these back,  

690
01:02:32,640 --> 01:02:36,160
but when you look at what they're doing 
on 3 nm with Rubin, some of those things  

691
01:02:36,160 --> 01:02:42,160
are simply not possible to do all the way back 
on A100, even if you make a new chip for 7 nm. 

692
01:02:42,160 --> 01:02:46,560
There are certain architectural improvements 
you can port and certain ones you cannot. 

693
01:02:47,600 --> 01:02:50,880
The performance difference is not just 
going to be the difference in FLOPS. 

694
01:02:50,880 --> 01:02:56,000
It's in some senses cumulative between 
the difference in FLOPS per chip,  

695
01:02:56,000 --> 01:03:00,000
networking speed between chips, how many FLOPS 
are on a chip versus a system, and memory  

696
01:03:00,000 --> 01:03:03,920
bandwidth on a single chip versus an entire 
system. All of these things compound. 

697
01:03:03,920 --> 01:03:10,720
Can I ask you a very naive question?
The B200 now has two dies on a single chip,  

698
01:03:10,720 --> 01:03:16,080
so you can get that bandwidth without 
having to go through NVLink or InfiniBand. 

699
01:03:16,080 --> 01:03:19,360
Next year, Rubin Ultra will 
have four dies on one chip. 

700
01:03:19,360 --> 01:03:24,480
What is preventing us from just doing 
that with an older… How many dies could  

701
01:03:24,480 --> 01:03:28,080
you have on a single chip and still 
get these tens of terabytes a second? 

702
01:03:28,880 --> 01:03:32,720
Even within Blackwell, there are differences in  

703
01:03:32,720 --> 01:03:36,240
performance when you're communicating 
on the chip versus across the chips. 

704
01:03:36,800 --> 01:03:41,520
Those bounds are obviously much smaller than 
when you're going out of the entire chip. 

705
01:03:45,200 --> 01:03:50,560
When you scale the number of chips 
up, there is some performance loss. 

706
01:03:50,560 --> 01:03:54,400
It's not perfect, but it is way 
better than different entire packages. 

707
01:03:54,400 --> 01:03:59,392
How large can advanced packaging scale?
The way Nvidia is doing it is CoWoS. 

708
01:04:01,040 --> 01:04:07,360
Google, Broadcom, MediaTek, and 
Amazon's Trainium are all doing CoWoS. 

709
01:04:07,360 --> 01:04:15,760
But actually you can go look back at what Tesla 
did with Dojo, which they cancelled and restarted. 

710
01:04:16,960 --> 01:04:19,680
Dojo was a chip that was 
the size of an entire wafer. 

711
01:04:19,680 --> 01:04:26,080
They had 25 chips on it. There were some 
tradeoffs. They couldn't put HBM on it. 

712
01:04:26,080 --> 01:04:29,760
But the positive side was 
that they had 25 chips on it. 

713
01:04:30,400 --> 01:04:34,560
To date, it is still probably the best chip 
for running convolutional neural networks. 

714
01:04:35,280 --> 01:04:41,360
It's just not great at transformers because the 
shape of the chip, the memory, the arithmetic,  

715
01:04:41,360 --> 01:04:45,040
and all these various specifications are just 
not well-suited for transformers. They're  

716
01:04:45,040 --> 01:04:52,800
well-suited for CNNs. Dojo chips were optimized 
around that, and they made a bigger package. 

717
01:04:52,800 --> 01:04:59,680
But as you make packages bigger and bigger, 
you have other constraints: networking speed,  

718
01:04:59,680 --> 01:05:03,520
memory bandwidth, and cooling capabilities.
All of these things start to rear their heads.  

719
01:05:03,520 --> 01:05:08,080
It's not simple. But yes, you will see a trend 
line of more chips on the package, and yes,  

720
01:05:08,080 --> 01:05:11,600
you're going to be able to do that on 7 nm.
In fact, that's what Huawei did  

721
01:05:11,600 --> 01:05:19,840
with their Ascend 910C or D.
They initially put one, and then they did two. 

722
01:05:20,720 --> 01:05:23,360
They're focusing on scaling the 
packaging up because that is an  

723
01:05:23,360 --> 01:05:28,080
area where they can advance faster than 
process technology where they can't shrink. 

724
01:05:28,080 --> 01:05:32,000
But at the end of the day, that’s something 
you can do on the leading-edge chips too. 

725
01:05:32,000 --> 01:05:35,840
Anything you do on 7 nm, you can also 
probably do on 3 nm in terms of packaging. 

726
01:05:36,800 --> 01:05:42,880
If we end up in this world in 2030 where the 
West has the most advanced process technology  

727
01:05:42,880 --> 01:05:48,240
but has not ramped it up as much, whereas 
China… I don't know if you think by 2030  

728
01:05:48,240 --> 01:05:53,680
they would have EUV and 2 nm or whatever.
But they are semiconductor-pilled and they  

729
01:05:53,680 --> 01:05:57,680
are producing in mass quantity.
Basically, I'm wondering what  

730
01:05:57,680 --> 01:06:03,040
the year is where there's a crossover, where our 
advantage in process technology has faded enough,  

731
01:06:03,040 --> 01:06:09,120
and their advantage in scale has increased enough.
And also, if their advantage in having one country  

732
01:06:09,120 --> 01:06:13,600
with the entire supply chain indigenized—rather 
than having random suppliers in Germany  

733
01:06:13,600 --> 01:06:21,360
and the Netherlands—would mean that China would 
be ahead in its ability to produce mass flops. 

734
01:06:22,080 --> 01:06:28,640
To date, China still does not have an entirely 
indigenized semiconductor supply chain. 

735
01:06:28,640 --> 01:06:32,960
But would they in 2030?
By 2030, it's possible that they do. 

736
01:06:33,520 --> 01:06:41,120
But to date, all of China's 7 nm and 
14 nm capacity uses ASML DUV tools. 

737
01:06:42,960 --> 01:06:46,560
The amount that they can 
import from ASML is large. 

738
01:06:47,200 --> 01:06:54,560
But the vast majority of ASML's revenue, 
especially on EUV all of it, is outside of China. 

739
01:06:54,560 --> 01:06:58,640
The scale advantage is still in 
the favor of the West plus Taiwan,  

740
01:06:58,640 --> 01:06:59,760
Japan, and Korea, et cetera.
But they're trying to make  

741
01:06:59,760 --> 01:07:03,040
their own DUV and EUV tools, right?
They're trying to do all these things. 

742
01:07:03,040 --> 01:07:08,560
The question is how fast can they advance 
and scale up production as well as quality. 

743
01:07:08,560 --> 01:07:12,160
To date, we haven't seen that.
Now I'm quite bullish that they're  

744
01:07:12,160 --> 01:07:16,000
going to be able to do these things 
over the next five to ten years. 

745
01:07:16,000 --> 01:07:20,000
They will really scale up production 
and kick it into high gear. 

746
01:07:20,000 --> 01:07:24,720
