908
01:21:46,320 --> 01:21:53,680
When you look at DDR, in that same 
area, it's maybe 64 or 128 bits wide. 

909
01:21:53,680 --> 01:22:01,840
That DDR5 is transferring at anywhere from 
6.4 to maybe 8,000 giga-transfers a second. 

910
01:22:01,840 --> 01:22:07,760
So your bandwidth is significantly lower.
It's 64 times 8,000 divided by  

911
01:22:07,760 --> 01:22:14,000
eight, which puts you at 64 gigabytes a second.
Even if you take a generous interpretation of  

912
01:22:14,000 --> 01:22:18,800
128 times 8 giga-transfers, you're at 128 
gigabytes a second for the same shoreline,  

913
01:22:18,800 --> 01:22:21,760
versus 2.5 terabytes a second.
There's an order of magnitude  

914
01:22:21,760 --> 01:22:27,520
difference in bandwidth per edge area.
If your chip is a square, or 26 by 33  

915
01:22:27,520 --> 01:22:32,080
millimeters—which is the maximum size for an 
individual die—you only have so much edge area. 

916
01:22:32,080 --> 01:22:34,480
On the inside of that chip, 
you put all your compute. 

917
01:22:34,480 --> 01:22:37,360
There are things you can do to try and 
change that, like more SRAM or more caching. 

918
01:22:38,240 --> 01:22:40,560
But at the end of the day, you're 
very constrained by bandwidth. 

