and mid-range smartphone volumes by half. 

960
01:25:52,720 --> 01:26:02,000
Yes, it’s only a $150 BOM increase on a $1,000 
iPhone where Apple has some larger margin. 

961
01:26:02,000 --> 01:26:08,720
But for smaller phones, the percentage of the BOM 
that goes to memory and storage is much larger. 

962
01:26:08,720 --> 01:26:13,760
And the margins are lower, so there's 
less capacity to even eat the margins. 

963
01:26:13,760 --> 01:26:17,840
And they have also generally tended not 
to do long-term agreements on memory. 

964
01:26:20,080 --> 01:26:26,880
Why this is a big deal is that if smartphone 
volumes halve, that drop will happen in  

965
01:26:26,880 --> 01:26:31,040
the low and mid-range, not the high end.
So it’s not like the bits released are halving. 

966
01:26:32,240 --> 01:26:35,280
Currently, consumer devices account 
for more than half of memory demand. 

967
01:26:35,280 --> 01:26:38,240
Even if you halve smartphone volumes, 
because of the shape of the halving,  

968
01:26:38,240 --> 01:26:42,080
the low end gets cut by more than half, while 
the high end gets cut by less than half,  

969
01:26:42,080 --> 01:26:46,000
because you and I will still buy the high-end 
phones that cost north of a thousand dollars. 

970
01:26:46,000 --> 01:26:48,320
We'll buy them even if they get 
a little bit more expensive. 

971
01:26:48,320 --> 01:26:52,080
And Apple's volumes will not go down as 
much as a low-end smartphone provider.  

972
01:26:52,640 --> 01:26:57,760
The same applies to PCs. What this 
does to the market is quite drastic. 

973
01:26:59,760 --> 01:27:06,240
DRAM gets released and goes to AI chips, who are 
willing to do longer-term contracts and pay higher  

974
01:27:06,240 --> 01:27:14,400
