They are, but not in as large quantities as DRAM. 

989
01:28:27,600 --> 01:28:32,480
Okay, so they will also increase because 
they'll be using some quantity, but there's  

990
01:28:32,480 --> 01:28:37,200
not as much of a need as there is for HBM. Makes 
sense. One thing I didn't appreciate until I was  

991
01:28:37,200 --> 01:28:43,920
reading some of your newsletters is that the 
same constraints preventing logic scaling over  

992
01:28:43,920 --> 01:28:49,600
the next few years are quite similar to what's 
preventing us from producing more memory wafers. 

993
01:28:49,600 --> 01:28:55,600
In fact, literally the same exact machine, 
this EUV tool, is needed for memory. 

994
01:28:55,600 --> 01:29:00,640
So I guess the question someone could ask right 
now is, why can't we just make more memory? 

995
01:29:05,680 --> 01:29:11,040
The constraints, as I was mentioning earlier, 
are not necessarily EUV tools today or next year. 

996
01:29:11,760 --> 01:29:14,960
They become that as we get to 
the latter part of the decade. 

997
01:29:15,600 --> 01:29:20,000
Currently, the constraints are more that 
they physically just haven't built fabs. 

998
01:29:20,000 --> 01:29:24,400
Over the last three to four years, 
these vendors have not built new fabs  

999
01:29:25,040 --> 01:29:29,440
