1303
01:56:07,200 --> 01:56:10,160
At the end of the day, I'm not 
exactly sure why they chose that site. 

1304
01:56:10,160 --> 01:56:16,000
I bet Elon would've chosen somewhere in 
Texas if he could've gone back because  

1305
01:56:16,000 --> 01:56:23,840
of the regulatory challenges he faced.
Ultimately, permitting is a challenge,  

1306
01:56:23,840 --> 01:56:27,600
but America is a big place with 50 
states, and things will get done. 

1307
01:56:27,600 --> 01:56:32,240
There are a lot of small jurisdictions where 
you can just transport in all the workers  

1308
01:56:32,240 --> 01:56:37,360
you need for a temporary period of three to 
twelve months, depending on the contractor. 

1309
01:56:37,360 --> 01:56:44,640
You can put them in temporary housing and pay out 
the butt, because labor is very cheap relative  

1310
01:56:44,640 --> 01:56:52,320
to the GPUs and the networking, and the end 
value of the tokens it's going to produce. 

1311
01:56:52,320 --> 01:56:53,440
So there is plenty of room to 
pay for all of these things. 

1312
01:56:59,520 --> 01:57:06,480
Also, people are also diversifying now.
Australia, Malaysia, Indonesia, and India  

1313
01:57:06,480 --> 01:57:09,440
are all places where data centers 
are going up at a much faster pace. 

1314
01:57:09,440 --> 01:57:12,560
But currently, over 70% of AI 
data centers are still in America,  

1315
01:57:12,560 --> 01:57:17,280
and that continues to be the trend.
People are figuring out how to build these things. 

1316
01:57:19,200 --> 01:57:22,240
Ultimately, dealing with permitting and 
red tape in middle-of-nowhere Texas,  

1317
01:57:23,280 --> 01:57:30,160
Wyoming, or New Mexico is probably a hell of 
a lot easier than sending stuff into space. 

1318
01:57:30,960 --> 01:57:36,560
Other than the economic argument making less sense 
once you consider that energy is a small fraction  

1319
01:57:36,560 --> 01:57:41,120
of the total cost of ownership of a data center, 
what are the other reasons you're skeptical? 

1320
01:57:41,920 --> 01:57:45,440
Obviously, power is basically free in space.
That's the reason to do it. 

1321
01:57:45,440 --> 01:57:48,320
Yeah, that's the reason to do it.
But there are all the other counterarguments. 

1322
01:57:50,560 --> 01:57:54,640
Even if power costs double on Earth, it's 
still a fraction of the total cost of the GPU. 

1323
01:57:54,640 --> 01:58:02,320
The main challenge is… We have 
ClusterMAX, which rates all the neoclouds. 

1324
01:58:03,200 --> 01:58:06,219
We test over 40 cloud companies, 
including the hyperscalers and neoclouds. 

1325
01:58:06,219 --> 01:58:11,360
Outside of software, what differentiates these 
clouds the most is their ability to deploy and  

1326
01:58:11,360 --> 01:58:19,200
manage failure. GPUs are horrendously unreliable. 
Even today, around 15% of Blackwells that get  

1327
01:58:19,200 --> 01:58:21,240
deployed have to be RMA'd.
You have to take them out. 

1328
01:58:21,240 --> 01:58:23,920
Sometimes you just have to plug them 
back in, but sometimes you have to take  

1329
01:58:23,920 --> 01:58:28,240
them out and ship them back to Nvidia or 
their partners who do the RMAs and such. 

1330
01:58:28,240 --> 01:58:34,320
What do you make of Elon's argument that after an 
initial phase, they actually don't fail that much? 

1331
01:58:34,320 --> 01:58:39,680
Sure, but now you've done this, tested them all, 
deconstructed them, put them on a spaceship,  

1332
01:58:39,680 --> 01:58:44,400
launched them into space, and then put 
them online again. That takes months. If  

1333
01:58:44,400 --> 01:58:57,680
your argument is that a GPU has a useful life of 
five years, and this takes six additional months,  

1334
01:58:57,680 --> 01:59:04,160
that is 10% of your cluster's useful life.
Because we're so capacity-constrained,  

1335
01:59:04,160 --> 01:59:08,960
that compute is theoretically most valuable 
in the first six months you have it. 

1336
01:59:08,960 --> 01:59:11,600
We're more constrained now 
than we will be in the future. 

1337
01:59:11,600 --> 01:59:15,120
That compute can contribute to a better 
model in the future, or generate revenue  

1338
01:59:15,120 --> 01:59:20,000
today that you can use to raise more money.
All these things make now the most important  

1339
01:59:20,000 --> 01:59:23,760
moment, but you've potentially delayed 
your compute deployment by six months. 

1340
01:59:25,120 --> 01:59:28,560
What separates these cloud providers is… We 
see some clouds taking six months to deploy  

1341
01:59:28,560 --> 01:59:31,280
GPUs right here on Earth.
We see clouds that take  

1342
01:59:31,280 --> 01:59:36,400
a lot less than six months.
So the question is, where does space get in there? 

1343
01:59:36,400 --> 01:59:41,280
I don't see how you could test them all on Earth, 
deconstruct them, and ship them to space without  

1344
01:59:41,280 --> 01:59:44,880
it taking significantly longer than just leaving 
them in the facility where you tested them. 

1345
01:59:45,440 --> 01:59:48,240
The question I wanted to ask is about 
the topology of space communication. 

1346
01:59:50,000 --> 01:59:56,240
Right now, Starlink satellites talk to 
each other at 100 gigabits per second. 

1347
01:59:56,240 --> 02:00:00,080
You could imagine that being much 
higher with optical intersatellite  

1348
02:00:00,080 --> 02:00:04,480
laser links optimized for this.
That actually ends up being quite  

1349
02:00:04,480 --> 02:00:09,200
close to InfiniBand bandwidth, 
which is 400 gigabytes a second. 

1350
02:00:09,200 --> 02:00:16,640
But that's per GPU, not per rack. So multiply 
that by 72. Also, that was Hopper. When you go  

1351
02:00:16,640 --> 02:00:24,480
to Blackwell and Rubin, that 2x's and 2x's again.
But how much compute is happening per… During  

1352
02:00:24,480 --> 02:00:27,360
inference, are the different scale-ups 
still working together, or is inference just  

1353
02:00:27,360 --> 02:00:33,440
happening as a batch within a single scale-up?
A lot of models fit within one scale-up domain,  

1354
02:00:33,440 --> 02:00:36,080
but many times you split them 
across multiple scale-up domains. 

1355
02:00:42,000 --> 02:00:48,400
As models become more and more sparse, 
which is the general trend, you want to  

1356
02:00:48,400 --> 02:00:53,280
ping just a couple of experts per GPU.
If leading models today have hundreds,  

1357
02:00:53,280 --> 02:00:59,680
if not a thousand, of experts, then you'd want to 
run this across hundreds or thousands of chips,  

1358
02:00:59,680 --> 02:01:05,120
even as we advance into the future.
So then you end up with the problem of  

1359
02:01:05,120 --> 02:01:08,960
needing to connect all these satellites 
together for communications as well. 

1360
02:01:09,760 --> 02:01:16,960
That would be tough. If there's a world where 
you could do inference for a batch on a single  

1361
02:01:17,600 --> 02:01:21,600
scale-up, then maybe it's more plausible.
But if not, it's a different story. 

1362
02:01:21,600 --> 02:01:24,400
Networking these chips together 
is a problem, and you can't just  

1363
02:01:24,400 --> 02:01:29,840
make the satellite infinitely large.
There are a lot of physics challenges to  

1364
02:01:29,840 --> 02:01:33,200
making a satellite really big.
That's why you need these  

1365
02:01:34,160 --> 02:01:38,880
interconnects between the satellites. Those 
interconnects are more expensive. In a cluster,  

1366
02:01:38,880 --> 02:01:43,600
15-20% of the cost is networking.
All of a sudden, you're using space lasers  

1367
02:01:43,600 --> 02:01:50,480
instead of simple lasers that are manufactured in 
volumes of millions with pluggable transceivers. 

1368
02:01:50,480 --> 02:01:54,160
And those things are very unreliable as well, 
more unreliable than the GPUs by the way. 

1369
02:01:54,160 --> 02:01:57,360
Across the life of a cluster, you have 
to unplug and clean them all the time. 

1370
02:01:57,360 --> 02:01:59,680
You have to unplug and replug 
them just for random reasons. 

1371
02:01:59,680 --> 02:02:03,280
These things are just not as reliable.
So you've got that problem as well. 

1372
02:02:03,280 --> 02:02:08,080
You've got a more expensive, complicated 
space laser to communicate instead of this  

1373
02:02:08,080 --> 02:02:11,040
pluggable optical transceiver that's 
been produced in super high volume. 

1374
02:02:11,040 --> 02:02:13,840
So all in all, what does that 
imply for space data centers? 

1375
02:02:13,840 --> 02:02:19,520
Space data centers effectively are 
not limited by their energy advantage. 

1376
02:02:19,520 --> 02:02:24,160
They are limited by the same contended resource.
We can only make two hundred gigawatts  

1377
02:02:24,160 --> 02:02:29,920
of chips a year by the end of the decade.
What are we going to do to get that capacity? 

1378
02:02:29,920 --> 02:02:36,000
It doesn't matter if it's on land or in space.
It doesn’t really matter,  

1379
02:02:36,000 --> 02:02:41,360
because you can build that power.
Human capabilities and capacity could get  

1380
02:02:41,360 --> 02:02:47,360
to the period where we're adding a terawatt 
a year globally of various types of power. 

1381
02:02:47,360 --> 02:02:52,240
At some point, we do cross the chasm where space 
data centers make sense, but it's not this decade. 

1382
02:02:52,960 --> 02:02:59,040
It is much further out, once energy 
constraints actually become a big bottleneck  

1383
02:02:59,040 --> 02:03:04,880
and land permitting becomes a much bigger 
bottleneck as it subsumes more of the economy. 

1384
02:03:04,880 --> 02:03:07,360
And crucially, once chips 
are no longer the bottleneck. 

1385
02:03:07,360 --> 02:03:11,440
Right now, chips are the biggest bottleneck.
You want them deployed and working on  

1386
02:03:11,440 --> 02:03:15,920
AI the moment they're manufactured.
There are a lot of things people are  

1387
02:03:15,920 --> 02:03:20,880
doing to increase that speed faster and faster.
They’re modularizing data centers, or even  

1388
02:03:20,880 --> 02:03:26,560
modularizing racks where you put the chip in at 
the data center, but only the chip and everything  

1389
02:03:26,560 --> 02:03:31,360
else is already wired up and ready to go.
There are things like this people are doing to  

1390
02:03:31,360 --> 02:03:36,400
decrease that time that you cannot do in space.
At the end of the day, all that matters in a  

1391
02:03:36,400 --> 02:03:40,720
chip-constrained world is getting 
these chips producing tokens ASAP. 

1392
02:03:43,200 --> 02:03:45,047
Maybe by 2035, the semiconductor industry, 
ASML, Zeiss, and suppliers like Lam  

1393
02:03:45,047 --> 02:03:53,040
Research and Applied Materials and other fab 
manufacturers will catch up once the pendulum  

1394
02:03:53,040 --> 02:03:58,000
swings and we are able to make enough chips.
Then we will be optimizing every dial and it makes  

1395
02:03:58,000 --> 02:04:03,840
sense to optimize the 10-15% of energy costs.
As we move to ASICs potentially,  

1396
02:04:03,840 --> 02:04:08,800
and if Nvidia's margins aren't +70%, maybe 
that energy cost becomes 30% of the cluster. 

1397
02:04:11,680 --> 02:04:18,640
These are the things to optimize.
But Elon doesn't win by doing 20% gains. He  

1398
02:04:18,640 --> 02:04:24,240
never wins that way. Elon wins when he swings for 
the fences and does 10X gains. That's what SpaceX  

1399
02:04:24,240 --> 02:04:30,880
is about. That's what Tesla is about. All of his 
success has been about that, not chasing the 20%. 

1400
02:04:31,520 --> 02:04:37,760
I think space data centers will eventually 
be a 10X gain as Earth's resources get more  

1401
02:04:37,760 --> 02:04:42,640
and more contentious, but that's not this decade.
Just to drive some intuition about how much land  

1402
02:04:42,640 --> 02:04:46,880
there is on Earth… Obviously, for the chips 
themselves, especially if you move to a world  

1403
02:04:46,880 --> 02:04:55,600
where you have racks that have megawatts—
That's the other thing. If manufacturing is  

1404
02:04:55,600 --> 02:05:00,160
the constraint, right now it's roughly one 
watt per square millimeter for AI chips. 

1405
02:05:01,920 --> 02:05:04,720
One easy way to improve that is to pump 
it to two watts per square millimeter. 

1406
02:05:05,280 --> 02:05:09,520
You may not get 2x the performance, 
you may only get 20% more performance,  

1407
02:05:09,520 --> 02:05:13,600
and that requires much more exotic cooling.
It requires more complicated cold plates  

1408
02:05:13,600 --> 02:05:18,240
and complex liquid cooling, or maybe 
even things like immersion cooling. 

1409
02:05:18,240 --> 02:05:20,560
In space, higher watts per 
millimeter is very difficult,  

1410
02:05:20,560 --> 02:05:25,760
whereas on Earth, these are solved problems.
One of these things enables you to get a lot  

1411
02:05:25,760 --> 02:05:31,840
more tokens, maybe 20% more tokens per wafer 
that's manufactured, and that's a humongous win. 

1412
02:05:31,840 --> 02:05:36,000
Square millimeter, you mean of die area?
Yeah, of die area. 

1413
02:05:36,640 --> 02:05:41,280
It would be better for space because more watts 
per millimeter means the chip runs hotter. 

1414
02:05:42,160 --> 02:05:46,640
I guess this is a question of computer 
chip engineering, but it cools to the  

1415
02:05:46,640 --> 02:05:49,920
fourth power by the Stefan-Boltzmann law.
If you can run a very hot  

1416
02:05:49,920 --> 02:05:51,920
chip, it allows a lot of—
No, you can't run it hotter. 

1417
02:05:51,920 --> 02:05:54,320
You can only run it denser.
The problem is that getting  

1418
02:05:54,320 --> 02:06:00,400
the heat out of that dense area means you have to 
move away from standard air and liquid cooling to  

1419
02:06:00,400 --> 02:06:04,960
more exotic forms of liquid cooling, or even 
immersion, to get to higher power densities. 

1420
02:06:05,600 --> 02:06:08,080
That's more difficult in 
space than it is on Earth. 

1421
02:06:08,640 --> 02:06:13,760
Maybe it's worth explaining at this point what 
exactly a scale-up is and what it looks like for  

1422
02:06:13,760 --> 02:06:22,720
Nvidia versus Trainium versus TPUs.
Earlier I was mentioning how  

1423
02:06:22,720 --> 02:06:26,640
communication within a chip is super fast.
Communication within chips that are in the  

1424
02:06:26,640 --> 02:06:30,720
same rack is fast, but not as fast.
It's on the order of terabytes. 

1425
02:06:30,720 --> 02:06:35,040
Communication very far away is on 
the order of hundreds of gigabytes. 

1426
02:06:36,560 --> 02:06:39,680
As you get further distance, maybe 
across the country, the order  

1427
02:06:39,680 --> 02:06:43,760
of magnitude is on the order of gigabytes.
A scale-up domain is this tight domain  

1428
02:06:44,320 --> 02:06:49,040
where the chips are communicating 
on the order of terabytes a second. 

1429
02:06:50,560 --> 02:06:55,040
For Nvidia, previously this meant 
an H100 server had eight GPUs,  

1430
02:06:55,040 --> 02:06:58,160
and those eight GPUs could talk to 
each other at terabytes a second. 

1431
02:06:58,160 --> 02:07:03,360
With Blackwell NVL72, they 
implemented rack-scale scale-up. 

1432
02:07:03,360 --> 02:07:08,480
That meant all seventy-two GPUs in the rack could 
connect to each other at terabytes a second. 

1433
02:07:09,040 --> 02:07:13,200
The speed doubled generation on generation, but 
the most important innovation was going from eight  

1434
02:07:13,200 --> 02:07:16,000
to seventy-two in the domain.
When we look at Google,  

1435
02:07:16,000 --> 02:07:20,960
their scale-up domain is completely different.
It has always been on the order of thousands. 

1436
02:07:20,960 --> 02:07:23,840
With TPU v4, they had pods the 
size of four thousand chips. 

1437
02:07:23,840 --> 02:07:29,760
With v8 or v7, they have pods in 
the eight or nine thousand range. 

1438
02:07:31,040 --> 02:07:35,200
What's relevant here is that it's not the 
same as Nvidia. It's not like for like.  

1439
02:07:35,200 --> 02:07:40,080
Google has a topology that's a torus.
Every chip connects to six neighbors.  

1440
02:07:40,080 --> 02:07:46,000
Nvidia's 72 GPUs connect all-to-all. 
They can send terabytes a second to  

1441
02:07:46,000 --> 02:07:51,200
any arbitrary other chip in that pod of scale-up.
Whereas Google, you have to bounce through chips. 

1442
02:07:52,080 --> 02:07:59,760
If TPU 1 needs to talk to TPU 76, it has to bounce 
through various chips, and there is always some  

1443
02:07:59,760 --> 02:08:04,800
blocking of resources when you do that because 
that one TPU is only connected to six other TPUs. 

1444
02:08:04,800 --> 02:08:07,200
So there is a difference 
in topology and bandwidth,  

1445
02:08:07,200 --> 02:08:11,200
and there are trade-offs and advantages to both.
Google gets to have a massive scale-up domain,  

1446
02:08:11,200 --> 02:08:15,760
but they have the trade-off of bouncing 
across chips to get from one to another. 

1447
02:08:15,760 --> 02:08:23,200
You can only talk to six direct neighbors.
Amazon has mutated their scale-up domain. 

1448
02:08:23,200 --> 02:08:28,240
They're somewhere in between Nvidia and Google.
They're trying to make larger scale-up domains. 

1449
02:08:28,880 --> 02:08:33,007
They try to do all-to-all to some extent with 
switches, which is what Nvidia does, but they also  

1450
02:08:33,007 --> 02:08:40,880
use torus topologies like Google to some extent.
As we advance forward to next generations,  

1451
02:08:40,880 --> 02:08:44,720
all three of them are moving more 
towards a dragonfly topology. 

1452
02:08:44,720 --> 02:08:49,680
That means there are some fully connected elements 
and some elements that are not fully connected. 

1453
02:08:49,680 --> 02:08:54,720
You can get the scale-up to be hundreds or 
thousands of chips, but also have it not contend  

1454
02:08:54,720 --> 02:09:00,960
for resources when bouncing through chips.
Related question: I heard somebody make the  

1455
02:09:00,960 --> 02:09:08,160
claim that the reason parameter scaling has been 
slow—and only now are we getting bigger models  

1456
02:09:08,160 --> 02:09:18,160
from OpenAI and Anthropic—is that… The original 
GPT-4 is over a trillion parameters, and only now  

1457
02:09:18,160 --> 02:09:24,400
are models starting to approach that again.
I heard a theory that the reason is that  

1458
02:09:24,400 --> 02:09:30,480
Nvidia's scale-ups have just not 
had that much memory capacity. 

1459
02:09:37,120 --> 02:09:42,640
Let's say you have a 5T model running at 
FP8, so that's five trillion gigabytes. 

1460
02:09:43,200 --> 02:09:47,440
And then you have the KV cache, let's say it's—
Just call it the same size. 

1461
02:09:47,440 --> 02:09:54,720
Okay, let's say it's the same size for one batch.
So you need ten terabytes to be able to run… 

1462
02:09:54,720 --> 02:09:59,600
A single forward pass, yeah.
And then only with the GB200 and NVL72  

1463
02:09:59,600 --> 02:10:03,680
do you have an Nvidia scale-up that has twenty 
terabytes, and before that they were much smaller. 

1464
02:10:03,680 --> 02:10:09,920
Whereas Google, on the other hand, has had 
these huge TPU pods that are not all-to-all,  

1465
02:10:09,920 --> 02:10:13,840
but still have hundreds of terabytes 
of capacity in a single scale-up. 

1466
02:10:13,840 --> 02:10:16,160
Does that explain why parameter 
scaling has been slow? 

1467
02:10:16,160 --> 02:10:22,000
I think it's partially the capacity and 
bandwidth, but also as you build a larger  

1468
02:10:22,000 --> 02:10:28,080
model, the ability to deploy it is slower.
In terms of what the inference speed is for  

1469
02:10:28,080 --> 02:10:33,680
the end user, that's kind of irrelevant. What's 
really relevant is RL. What we've seen with these  

1470
02:10:33,680 --> 02:10:38,560
models and allocation of compute at a lab… There 
are a few main ways you can allocate compute. 

1471
02:10:38,560 --> 02:10:42,640
You can allocate it to inference, i.e. revenue.
You can allocate it to development,  

1472
02:10:42,640 --> 02:10:45,280
i.e. making the next model.
You can allocate it to research. 

1473
02:10:46,400 --> 02:10:51,360
In development specifically, you 
split it between pre-training and RL. 

1474
02:10:52,880 --> 02:10:58,720
When you think about what is happening, the 
compute efficiency gains you get from research  

1475
02:10:58,720 --> 02:11:03,600
are so large that you actually want most of your 
compute to go to research, not to development. 

1476
02:11:04,640 --> 02:11:08,400
All these researchers are generating new 
ideas, trying them out, testing them,  

1477
02:11:08,400 --> 02:11:13,360
and continuing to push the Pareto optimal 
curve of scaling laws further and further. 

1478
02:11:14,800 --> 02:11:17,840
Empirically, what we’ve seen is that 
model costs get ten times cheaper  

1479
02:11:17,840 --> 02:11:22,480
every year, or even more than that.
At the same scale it gets ten times cheaper,  

1480
02:11:23,360 --> 02:11:26,480
and to reach new frontiers it 
costs the same amount or more. 

1481
02:11:27,840 --> 02:11:33,360
So you don't want to allocate too 
many resources to pre-training and RL. 

1482
02:11:33,360 --> 02:11:35,680
You actually want to allocate most 
of your resources to research. 

1483
02:11:36,560 --> 02:11:42,400
In the middle is this development period.
If you pre-train a five-trillion-parameter model,  

1484
02:11:45,600 --> 02:11:51,760
how many rollouts do you have to do in RL?
Rollouts for a five-trillion-parameter model  

1485
02:11:51,760 --> 02:11:54,640
are five times larger than for 
a one-trillion-parameter model. 

1486
02:11:54,640 --> 02:11:57,520
If you wanted to do as many rollouts—maybe 
the larger model is two times more sample  

1487
02:11:57,520 --> 02:12:04,640
efficient—now you need 2.5x as much 
time of RL to get the model smarter. 

1488
02:12:05,200 --> 02:12:12,160
